README.md
     1в†’# python-dotenv
     3в†’[![Build Status][build_status_badge]][build_status_link]
     4в†’[![PyPI version][pypi_badge]][pypi_link]
     5в†’
     6в†’python-dotenv reads key-value pairs from a `.env` file and can set them as
     7в†’environment variables. It helps in the development of applications following the
     8в†’[12-factor](https://12factor.net/) principles.
     9в†’
    10в†’- [Getting Started](#getting-started)
    11в†’- [Other Use Cases](#other-use-cases)
    12в†’  - [Load configuration without altering the environment](#load-configuration-without-altering-the-environment)
    13в†’  - [Parse configuration as a stream](#parse-configuration-as-a-stream)
    14в†’  - [Load .env files in IPython](#load-env-files-in-ipython)
    15в†’- [Command-line Interface](#command-line-interface)
    16в†’- [File format](#file-format)
    17в†’  - [Multiline values](#multiline-values)
    18в†’  - [Variable expansion](#variable-expansion)
    19в†’- [Related Projects](#related-projects)
    20в†’- [Acknowledgements](#acknowledgements)
    21в†’
    22в†’## Getting Started
    24в†’```shell
    25в†’pip install python-dotenv
    26в†’```
    27в†’
    28в†’If your application takes its configuration from environment variables, like a
    29в†’12-factor application, launching it in development is not very practical because
    30в†’you have to set those environment variables yourself.
    31в†’
    32в†’To help you with that, you can add python-dotenv to your application to make it
    33в†’load the configuration from a `.env` file when it is present (e.g. in
    34в†’development) while remaining configurable via the environment:
    35в†’
    36в†’```python
    37в†’from dotenv import load_dotenv
    38в†’
    39в†’load_dotenv()  # reads variables from a .env file and sets them in os.environ
    40в†’
    41в†’# Code of your application, which uses environment variables (e.g. from `os.environ` or
    42в†’# `os.getenv`) as if they came from the actual environment.
    43в†’```
    44в†’
    45в†’By default, `load_dotenv()` will:
    46в†’
    47в†’- Look for a `.env` file in the same directory as the Python script (or higher up the directory tree).
    48в†’- Read each key-value pair and add it to `os.environ`.
    49в†’- **Not override** existing environment variables (`override=False`). Pass `override=True` to override existing variables.
    50в†’
    51в†’To configure the development environment, add a `.env` in the root directory of
    52в†’your project:
    53в†’
    54в†’```
    55в†’.
    56в†’в”њв”Ђв”Ђ .env
    57в†’в””в”Ђв”Ђ foo.py
    58в†’```
    59в†’
    60в†’The syntax of `.env` files supported by python-dotenv is similar to that of
    61в†’Bash:
    62в†’
    63в†’```bash
    64в†’# Development settings
    65в†’DOMAIN=example.org
    66в†’ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@${DOMAIN}
    67в†’ROOT_URL=${DOMAIN}/app
    68в†’```
    69в†’
    70в†’If you use variables in values, ensure they are surrounded with `{` and `}`,
    71в†’like `${DOMAIN}`, as bare variables such as `$DOMAIN` are not expanded.
    72в†’
    73в†’You will probably want to add `.env` to your `.gitignore`, especially if it
    74в†’contains secrets like a password.
    75в†’
    76в†’See the section "[File format](#file-format)" below for more information about what you can write in a `.env` file.
    77в†’
    78в†’## Other Use Cases
    80в†’### Load configuration without altering the environment
    82в†’The function `dotenv_values` works more or less the same way as `load_dotenv`,
    83в†’except it doesn't touch the environment, it just returns a `dict` with the
    84в†’values parsed from the `.env` file.
    85в†’
    86в†’```python
    87в†’from dotenv import dotenv_values
    88в†’
    89в†’config = dotenv_values(".env")  # config = {"USER": "foo", "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"}
    90в†’```
    91в†’
    92в†’This notably enables advanced configuration management:
    93в†’
    94в†’```python
    95в†’import os
    96в†’from dotenv import dotenv_values
    97в†’
    98в†’config = {
    99в†’    **dotenv_values(".env.shared"),  # load shared development variables
   100в†’    **dotenv_values(".env.secret"),  # load sensitive variables
   101в†’    **os.environ,  # override loaded values with environment variables
   102в†’}
   103в†’```
   104в†’
   105в†’### Parse configuration as a stream
   107в†’`load_dotenv` and `dotenv_values` accept [streams][python_streams] via their
   108в†’`stream` argument. It is thus possible to load the variables from sources other
   109в†’than the filesystem (e.g. the network).
   110в†’
   111в†’```python
   112в†’from io import StringIO
   113в†’
   114в†’from dotenv import load_dotenv
   115в†’
   116в†’config = StringIO("USER=foo\nEMAIL=foo@example.org")
   117в†’load_dotenv(stream=config)
   118в†’```
   119в†’
   120в†’### Load .env files in IPython
   122в†’You can use dotenv in IPython. By default, it will use `find_dotenv` to search for a
   123в†’`.env` file:
   124в†’
   125в†’```python
   126в†’%load_ext dotenv
   127в†’%dotenv
   128в†’```
   129в†’
   130в†’You can also specify a path:
   131в†’
   132в†’```python
   133в†’%dotenv relative/or/absolute/path/to/.env
   134в†’```
   135в†’
   136в†’Optional flags:
   137в†’
   138в†’- `-o` to override existing variables.
   139в†’- `-v` for increased verbosity.
   140в†’
   141в†’### Disable load_dotenv
   143в†’Set `PYTHON_DOTENV_DISABLED=1` to disable `load_dotenv()` from loading .env
   144в†’files or streams. Useful when you can't modify third-party package calls or in
   145в†’production.
   146в†’
   147в†’## Command-line Interface
   149в†’A CLI interface `dotenv` is also included, which helps you manipulate the `.env`
   150в†’file without manually opening it.
   151в†’
   152в†’```shell
   153в†’$ pip install "python-dotenv[cli]"
   154в†’$ dotenv set USER foo
   155в†’$ dotenv set EMAIL foo@example.org
   156в†’$ dotenv list
   157в†’USER=foo
   158в†’EMAIL=foo@example.org
   159в†’$ dotenv list --format=json
   160в†’{
   161в†’  "USER": "foo",
   162в†’  "EMAIL": "foo@example.org"
   163в†’}
   164в†’$ dotenv run -- python foo.py
   165в†’```
   166в†’
   167в†’Run `dotenv --help` for more information about the options and subcommands.
   168в†’
   169в†’## File format
   171в†’The format is not formally specified and still improves over time. That being
   172в†’said, `.env` files should mostly look like Bash files. Reading from FIFOs (named
   173в†’pipes) on Unix systems is also supported.
   174в†’
   175в†’Keys can be unquoted or single-quoted. Values can be unquoted, single- or
   176в†’double-quoted. Spaces before and after keys, equal signs, and values are
   177в†’ignored. Values can be followed by a comment. Lines can start with the `export`
   178в†’directive, which does not affect their interpretation.
   179в†’
   180в†’Allowed escape sequences:
   181в†’
   182в†’- in single-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`
   183в†’- in double-quoted values: `\\`, `\'`, `\"`, `\a`, `\b`, `\f`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, `\v`
   184в†’
   185в†’### Multiline values
   187в†’It is possible for single- or double-quoted values to span multiple lines. The
   188в†’following examples are equivalent:
   189в†’
   190в†’```bash
   191в†’FOO="first line
   192в†’second line"
   193в†’```
   194в†’
   195в†’```bash
   196в†’FOO="first line\nsecond line"
   197в†’```
   198в†’
   199в†’### Variable without a value
   201в†’A variable can have no value:
   202в†’
   203в†’```bash
   204в†’FOO
   205в†’```
   206в†’
   207в†’It results in `dotenv_values` associating that variable name with the value
   208в†’`None` (e.g. `{"FOO": None}`. `load_dotenv`, on the other hand, simply ignores
   209в†’such variables.
   210в†’
   211в†’This shouldn't be confused with `FOO=`, in which case the variable is associated
   212в†’with the empty string.
   213в†’
   214в†’### Variable expansion
   216в†’python-dotenv can interpolate variables using POSIX variable expansion.
   217в†’
   218в†’With `load_dotenv(override=True)` or `dotenv_values()`, the value of a variable
   219в†’is the first of the values defined in the following list:
   220в†’
   221в†’- Value of that variable in the `.env` file.
   222в†’- Value of that variable in the environment.
   223в†’- Default value, if provided.
   224в†’- Empty string.
   225в†’
   226в†’With `load_dotenv(override=False)`, the value of a variable is the first of the
   227в†’values defined in the following list:
   228в†’
   229в†’- Value of that variable in the environment.
   230в†’- Value of that variable in the `.env` file.
   231в†’- Default value, if provided.
   232в†’- Empty string.
   233в†’
